Name: Waters, Maxine
text: Today, I am concentrating on everything that I and our governments can do to stop the fires that are devastating our communities of the Pacific Palisades of West Los Angeles, Malibu, the Eaton Fire north of Pasadena, and the Hurst Fire in the San Fernando Valley, as well as other areas that may also be affected such as Santa Monica. These fires have already reaped tremendous devastation on the homes and families of these areas, and I am praying that our frontline firefighters will be able to contain these fires as soon as possible. Already, 80,000 people or more have been evacuated, and even more families may have to be evacuated. Despite the horror and devastation of these fires, I encourage the families to obey the instructions of all of our frontline workers and do whatever is necessary to save lives. President Biden has assured members of Congress that the White House is doing anything and everything possible, and we have already started the discussion about the financial devastation that has taken place and what will be the tremendous need for appropriations to deal with the recovery. I strongly support a bipartisan, bicameral effort to do everything possible to give real assistance to all of the neighborhoods of Los Angeles County and beyond if necessary. For further information, please call 800-927-4357.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1945, General Douglas MacArthur and the American 6th Army landed at Lingayen Gulf on Luzon, marking a significant step in retaking the Philippines from Japan. 

The Japanese had controlled the islands since May 1942, after American forces were defeated and MacArthur was forced to leave. However, in October 1944, over 100,000 American troops landed on Leyte Island, leading to one of the bloodiest battles of the Pacific war and signaling Japan‚Äôs impending defeat.

This victory paved the way for an American landing of over 60,000 troops on Luzon. Despite little initial opposition, Japanese kamikazes struck U.S. vessels, killing 49 American sailors. As American forces advanced, they discovered a network of Japanese caves and tunnels designed to lure them inland. The Japanese fought fiercely, hoping to delay the American push toward Japan. Despite their resistance, the U.S. ultimately secured Luzon and, with it, control of the Philippines.

Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
text:
üá∫üá∏ GULF OF AMERICA BILL INTRODUCED üá∫üá∏

Today, I officially introduced my bill to rename the Gulf of Mexico the Gulf of America.

Mexican cartels currently use the Gulf of Mexico to traffic humans, drugs, weapons, and God knows what else while the Mexican government allows them to do it.

The American people are footing the bill to protect and secure the maritime waterways for commerce to be conducted. Our U.S. armed forces protect the area from any military threats from foreign countries.

It‚Äôs our gulf. The rightful name is the Gulf of America and it‚Äôs what the entire world should refer to it as.

Immediately following President Trump‚Äôs announcement, I directed my staff to get the bill drafted. I submitted the bill this afternoon with 14 original cosponsors.

My bill directs the Chairman of the Board on Geographic Names under the Secretary of the Interior to rename all federal documents and maps within 180 days of being signed into law.

Congress has to take the Trump Agenda mandate seriously and that means acting fast to enact it.

This is a piece of Day 1 legislation that can easily be awaiting President Trump‚Äôs signature the moment he takes his oath of office.

I urge my colleagues to join me to quickly pass this bill.

Name: McCormick, Richard
text:
It was an honor to attend the memorial service for Former President James Earl Carter, Jr. Not only did he serve as the 39th President of the United States, but he also served as the 76th governor of Georgia.

Carter is well known for his philanthropic efforts after his presidency. He was a Nobel Peace Prize winner in 2002 for his tireless efforts to resolve international conflicts and advance democracy and human rights. After his presidency, he founded the Carter Center, a nonpartisan public policy center in Atlanta. Carter also championed Habitat for Humanity, a Georgia-based charity that helps those in need build new homes or renovate older ones.

May he rest in peace.

Name: Mills, Cory
text:
I am proud to co-lead H.R. 253, the Bipartisan Restoring Faith in Government Act,  alongside Representatives @RepBrianFitz (PA-01), @RepAOC (NY-14), and @CongressmanRaja (IL-08).

Members of Congress should not trade stocks, plain and simple. There have been far too many instances where elected officials have profited millions through practices that would land any regular American in prison for insider trading. This blatant double standard erodes trust in our government and must come to an end.

I am proud to work alongside my colleagues on the Bipartisan Restoring Faith in Government Act, which will ban stock trading for Members of Congress, their spouses, and dependents, a bipartisan commitment to restore transparency and integrity.

Elected officials are entrusted to serve the American people, not to line their own pockets. This bill is a necessary step to guarantee that we prioritize the interests of our constituencies, not members' personal stock portfolios.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 1/ Let‚Äôs set the record straight on the Laken Riley Act, because I‚Äôm hearing a lot of people who say they support this bill, but who don't seem to know what it really does.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 4/ This bill also lets state attorneys general like Ken Paxton in Texas go to court and overturn decisions made by immigration judges and ICE officers ‚Äî and even ask a court to block legal immigration from entire countries.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 2/ First things first, if you are undocumented and arrested or convicted of a felony, you're already subject to detention and deportation. That‚Äôs already on the books. It‚Äôs a good law, I agree with it, and it should be enforced.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 3/ That‚Äôs not what this bill is about. This bill targets people who have been accused of shoplifting. Not rapists and murderers like the monster who killed Laken Riley. People accused of shoplifting.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 5/ This is a trojan horse bill that exploits Laken Riley's tragic murder in order to dramatically expand the government‚Äôs power to shut down LEGAL immigration & detain people who are not convicted of any crime at all.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 6/ For example, if this bill is signed into law, a 12-year-old kid brought here by a parent could be LOCKED IN ICE DETENTION if they are accused‚Äînot even convicted, simple accused‚Äîof stealing a candy bar.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 7/ A DACA or TPS recipient who has LEGAL status could be detained indefinitely just because they are misidentified in a police lineup. So much for the presumption of innocence.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text:
10/ And despite all the problems in this bill, Democrats still wanted to work to improve it. 

We were shut out by Republicans who let us offer ZERO amendments to try to make it better.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text:
11/ I‚Äôd love to work together on actual solutions to keep our country safe and secure our border.

Sadly, all we get is a bill designed to score political soundbites and accuse Democrats of ‚Äúvoting to keep murderers and rapists in our country illegally‚Äù. Which is a lie.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text:
9/ Congress had the chance to enact a tough, strong, bipartisan immigration and border security bill last year. 

It was written by the most conservative, pro-MAGA people. 

Suddenly, it was abandoned. Because Donald Trump didn‚Äôt want bipartisanship on border security.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 8/ This bill is political grandstanding at its worst. Republicans are exploiting Laken Riley‚Äôs murder to play Washington games while refusing to actually do anything about America's broken border and failed immigration system.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text:

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 49 BC, Julius Caesar's crossing of the Rubicon River marked a critical turning point in Roman history, signaling the end of the Roman Republic and the rise of the Roman Empire. 

When Caesar's term in Gaul ended, the Senate demanded that he disband his army and return to Rome as a private citizen or be declared an enemy of the state. This put Caesar in a vulnerable position, as he could face prosecution for actions during his consulship and campaigns. Caesar chose to act, crossing the Rubicon with his army during the night. By doing so, he declared war on Rome, uttering the phrase "Alea iacta est" ("The die is cast").

This bold move ignited a civil war, culminating in Caesar's victory. He seized control of Rome and ruled as dictator for life. The phrase "crossing the Rubicon" has since become a metaphor for taking an irreversible, decisive step.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First

Tammy Daniel, a Wilson resident and dedicated advocate for youth empowerment, has spent over 15 years working to transform the lives of young people in her community. As the executive director of Y.O.U.T.H. of Wilson County (Youth Oriented Understanding Through Help), Tammy has passionately worked to rehabilitate juvenile offenders and provide positive role models for at-risk youth.

Through her leadership, Tammy has helped many young people who were once at risk of falling through the cracks. She has witnessed firsthand how early intervention and positive adult relationships can change a life.

Tammy is deeply involved in the Wilson community, offering a safe space for youth to receive hands-on mentoring and redirection when necessary. Her impact is felt through the success of the individuals she serves and in the community, where she continues to foster growth, accountability, and positive change.

#FridaySpotlight

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we celebrate the stories of Hometown Heroes from across our district‚Äîremarkable individuals whose actions ripple outward and go beyond the ordinary. Today, we shine a light on a man who has dedicated his life to our safety, our justice, and our community. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero: Pat McGinty of Middletown Township.

For nearly four decades, Pat McGinty stood as a protector and cornerstone of our community. From the moment he first pinned on the badge in 1974, Pat embraced a calling that was not just a job, but a profound commitment to serve. As a patrolman, K-9 detective, lieutenant, sergeant, and acting public safety director, he didn‚Äôt just uphold the law‚Äîhe wove himself into the very fabric of Middletown Township, becoming a beacon of safety, justice, and compassion.

Pat‚Äôs dedication went far beyond the routine duties of a police officer. He carried the weight of some of our community‚Äôs darkest moments, always rising to meet the call with integrity and resolve. Whether it was reopening cold cases to bring long-overdue justice to grieving families, ensuring that no rookie officer bore the emotional burden of a death notification alone, or leading the investigation of the tragic loss of Newtown Police Officer Brian Gregg in 2005, Pat approached every challenge with a steady hand and a compassionate heart. He understood that behind every case, every tragedy, there were human lives‚Äîfamilies yearning for closure, communities yearning for healing.

A graduate of the FBI's National Academy, a prestigious training course in Quantico, Va., for law enforcement leaders across the globe, he earned the respect of law enforcement leaders across the country, while never losing sight of the community he served at home. He was a mentor to fellow officers, a guide to those starting their careers, and a symbol of excellence in law enforcement. Pat elevated those around him, creating a legacy of leadership that continues to shape the next generation of our officers.

But perhaps what speaks most to Pat‚Äôs character is his humility. He never sought recognition or accolades. For Pat, service was its own reward. Even after his retirement in 2011, he continued to give back, working in juvenile fingerprinting and DNA analysis at the Doylestown Courthouse.

This past Saturday, as a parade of officers and firefighters from across our region came together to honor Pat, it was clear just how deeply he is woven into the heart of this community. Recently diagnosed with an aggressive form of terminal cancer, Pat reminded us of the profound truth of his life‚Äôs work: ‚ÄúThe impact of this work reaches far beyond the badge.‚Äù

Pat McGinty hasn‚Äôt just serve our community‚Äîhe has shaped it. He has stood with us in times of joy and sorrow, in moments of triumph and tragedy. He has been more than a law enforcement officer; he has been a guardian of our safety, a champion of justice, and a steadfast presence in our lives. His legacy is not written in medals or titles, but in the countless lives he has touched, the peace he has preserved, and the community he has helped protect.

To Pat‚Äôs beloved wife Nancy, his children, and his grandchildren: your sacrifices and unwavering support have been a cornerstone of Pat‚Äôs service. You have shared him with all of us, and for that, we are forever grateful.

Pat, you are more than a hero‚Äîyou are a symbol of what it means to give everything for the good of others. On behalf of an immensely grateful community, thank you for your service, your sacrifice, and your steadfast dedication to making our world a better, safer place. May God bless you and your family, and know that your lifetime of service will continue to inspire our community forever.

Name: Flood, Mike
text: Politicians have blamed the insurance industry for their troubles. The truth is private carriers were forced out of California due to government mandates that do not allow the industry to appropriately price for risk and costs.

Name: Flood, Mike
text: As the incoming Chairman of the Housing and Insurance Subcommittee on @FinancialCmte, I am monitoring the impact of the California wildfires closely. I‚Äôm very concerned. Impacted homeowners are about to grapple with another crisis looming over the state: California‚Äôs home insurance market.

Name: Flood, Mike
text: Additionally, California‚Äôs requirement that carriers have to seek state approval before adjusting pricing, which in many cases takes months if approved at all, has distorted the insurance market and made it very difficult for carriers to offer consumers the products they need to protect their homes.

Name: Flood, Mike
text: While our state-based insurance model has long been successful, it is not immune to misguided policy choices, particularly in states with liberals and progressives in positions of power. California has consistently been the prime offender, with the Insurance Commissioner enacting onerous mandates and refusing to allow insurance companies to incorporate the cost of reinsurance or use standard industry practices like catastrophe models to predict future risk.

Name: Flood, Mike
text: In response to this affordability and availability crisis last month, California‚Äôs Insurance Commissioner finally allowed for the few remaining insurance firms in state to use catastrophe pricing and price in reinsurance in policy writing. While these reforms are welcome, more action is needed to foster competition, entice carriers to return, and ensure policyholders, and ultimately, taxpayers are not paying for the mistakes of California bureaucrats.

Name: Flood, Mike
text: These misguided decisions have pushed out private insurance firms, forcing more homeowners into California‚Äôs FAIR plan, the state‚Äôs insolvent fire insurance pool of last resort. FAIR‚Äôs exposure has tripled to $458 billion as of last September, with only $700 million cash on hand to pay claims.

Name: Flood, Mike
text: Concerns have grown that the claim costs on these devastating fires will bankrupt the FAIR pool of funds, with private insurers and their policyholders on the hook for covering the excess claims. This comes on top of the already high costs many consumers face due to California‚Äôs other poor state regulatory choices.

Name: Flood, Mike
text: California has placed political preferences ahead of sound actuarial principles for far too long, harming consumers as costs go up and availability goes down. As Congress assesses the damage, debates the recovery, and supports the people of California, I will strongly advocate for policies that adhere to risk-based pricing principles to support consumers and taxpayers.

Name: Flood, Mike
text: While these are appropriate roles for Congress, the root issues won‚Äôt be solved by Washington. California is going to have to make changes to fix its broken home insurance market. As the incoming Chairman of the Housing and Insurance Subcommittee on the HFSC, there will be a full accounting of California‚Äôs broken insurance market as the recovery cost figures begin to emerge.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Yes, Gen Z, we get it‚Äîyou don‚Äôt care about data privacy. But that‚Äôs just a tiny part of the story.

The real issue here is control. The Chinese Communist Party is using TikTok to build a blueprint of influence over you and our society. They‚Äôre not just tracking what you do; they‚Äôre deciding what you see, and therefore *how you think*. There is plenty of evidence this is already happening.

Now imagine how much more powerful it would be as an information warfare weapon when the proverbial shit hits the fan in a potential conflict over Taiwan. Yeah, the Chinese will take control of all advanced semi-conductor chips in Taiwan (the ones that power your precious smartphone), and then use your addiction to TikTok to convince you it‚Äôs all a good idea.

TikTok, as an entertainment platform, is an incredible product. It‚Äôs fun, it‚Äôs creative, and millions of Americans love using it. But we also need to recognize that it‚Äôs a Trojan horse. And right now, that horse is carrying Chinese Communist Party influence into our backyard and sending American‚Äôs data back to Beijing. That‚Äôs the problem we need to solve.

The goal here is not about trying to stop American small businesses who use TikTok to promote themselves, the latest dances, or end ‚Äúbrain rot‚Äù trends‚Äîthough maybe fixing that wouldn‚Äôt hurt either. It‚Äôs about making sure that enjoyment doesn‚Äôt come at the cost of our privacy, our freedom, or our national security.

There‚Äôs a way to fix this. We don‚Äôt need to kill TikTok; we need to kick the Chinese Communist Party out of it. Ownership by someone who shares‚Äîor at least respects‚Äîour democratic values is the solution. People like Kevin O‚ÄôLeary from Shark Tank and Dodgers owner Frank McCourt are already exploring a potential acquisition. But the fact that TikTok seems unwilling to even consider this solution tells us all we need to know about its true purpose.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1908, President Theodore Roosevelt declared the Grand Canyon a national monument, protecting over 800,000 acres of the iconic landmark in northwestern Arizona. 

While Native Americans had lived in the area for centuries, it wasn‚Äôt until 1869 that geologist John Wesley Powell led the first challenging journey through the canyon, navigating the Colorado River.

By the late 19th century, the Grand Canyon had become a popular tourist destination, attracting figures like Roosevelt, who had a deep appreciation for the American West. Roosevelt famously stated, ‚ÄúLet this great wonder of nature remain as it now is‚Ä¶ what you can do is keep it for your children, your children‚Äôs children, and all who come after you.‚Äù

Congress officially made the Grand Canyon a national park in 1919, banning private development. Today, over 5 million visitors annually explore the canyon, enjoying activities like hiking, whitewater rafting, and taking in views from the South Rim, which remains largely unchanged for over four centuries.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 27 BC, the Roman Empire began. 

Having already triumphed over Mark Antony and Cleopatra, Octavian, Julius Caesar‚Äôs son and Rome‚Äôs ruler, realized the Roman people did not prefer a monarchy. In a strategic move, Octavian appeared before the Senate and, in a symbolic gesture, formally relinquished his powers, returning authority to the Senate and the citizens of Rome. 

However, this act was largely ceremonial. In response, the Senate granted him control over key provinces such as Spain, Gaul, and Syria. Octavian effectively retained ultimate power while maintaining the fa√ßade of a republican system.

I am disappointed that the Supreme Court denied Utah the opportunity to make its case and challenge the federal government‚Äôs ownership of nearly 70% of Utah lands. 

It is unfortunate that the Court currently views cases like this one as part of its discretionary docket‚Äîcontrary to the plain language of the relevant statute. But the fight for local control and state sovereignty is far from over, and this setback doesn‚Äôt preclude the state from making these arguments in a lower court. 

The people of Utah deserve to have greater access to 2/3 of the land in our state‚Äîwhether for recreation, natural resources, building new homes for hardworking families, or otherwise. 

I will keep fighting for legislation that will give America back to Americans, especially those from public-land states.

As Chair of the Working Families Tax Team, I‚Äôve been working with community members in PA-1 and across the nation to understand the real impact of these policies and the message is clear‚Äîthey need support, not setbacks.

‚û°Ô∏è The Child Tax Credit will be slashed in half‚Äîfrom $2,000 to $1,000 per child‚Äîimpacting 40 million families and placing an even greater burden on those already struggling to make ends meet.

Protecting and strengthening the Child Tax Credit is not just the right thing to do; it‚Äôs essential for the future of our children and our nation.
